<div class="container">
  <!-- Style guide notes go here -->

  <div class="row-fluid styleguide-notes">

    <div class="styleguide-wrapper">
      <div class="span12">
        <div class="content-container styleguide-container">
          <h1>Styleguide notes</h1>
          <hr />
          <h2>Search</h2>
          <hr />

          <div class="content-container">
            <h3>Usage</h3>
            <p>Only products can be searched</p>
            <h4>Interactions</h4>
            <p>Users can enter search terms in the form field. Prompt text is provided via the HTML placeholder attribute, this does not appear in older browsers. </p>
            <h4>Layout modes</h4>
            <p>There are two layout modes: desktop, tablet and mobile. Larger screens provide a search facility in the top utilities bar alongside the breadcrumb, smaller screens have the search bar hidden and accessible by a button to open the container</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>CSS</h3>
            <h4>Media queries</h4>
            <p>We are using three breakpoints to handle the changes between desktop, tablet and mobile. Common styles are loaded for the component and then device specific styles are loaded in for each breakpoint into the appropriate stylesheet.</p>
            <h4>SASS Partials</h4>
            <p>You can find the CSS for this component in the following SASS Partials:</p>
            <p>/common-components/product-search.scss</p>
            <p>/large-components/product-search.scss</p>
            <p>/small-components/product-search.scss</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Use of Javascript</h3>
            <p>Javascript is used to append a button to the mobile listing template and hide the search container. A click event is bound to the button to toggle the visibility of the search container</p>
            <h4>Non-JS behaviour</h4>
            <p>The mobile search container is already visible to users.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Component variants</h3>
            <p>The search panel appears on the product listing and product description templates. On the product description templates it is visible at all times and not hidden on mobile.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Accessibility</h3>
            <p>This element contains a form field. It requires a label/input pair with a correctly populated unique for/id value.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

